"Vile M.A., Bridgham S.D., Wieder R.K., Novák M.","Atmospheric sulfur deposition alters pathways of gaseous carbon production in peatlands",2003,"Global Biogeochemical Cycles","17","2",,"27","1",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0042238352&partnerID=40&md5=2ec51a19df4cfbaf35541a5401300a11","Department of Biological Siences, University of Notre Dame, Notre Dame, IN, United States; Department of Biology, Villanova University, Villanova, PA 19085, United States; Czech Geological Survey, Geologická 6, Praha 5 152 00, Czech Republic","Vile, M.A., Department of Biological Siences, University of Notre Dame, Notre Dame, IN, United States; Bridgham, S.D., Department of Biological Siences, University of Notre Dame, Notre Dame, IN, United States; Wieder, R.K., Department of Biology, Villanova University, Villanova, PA 19085, United States; Novák, M., Czech Geological Survey, Geologická 6, Praha 5 152 00, Czech Republic","Peatlands represent large carbon (C) reservoirs that can act as a source or sink for greenhouse gases. The response of peatland gaseous C fluxes to global climate change and atmospheric sulfate deposition, however, remains uncertain. Methanogenesis is thought to be one of the most important anaerobic C mineralization pathways in peatlands, especially in regions where input of sulfate from acid deposition is low. However, sulfate reduction has been quantified rarely in freshwater wetlands. Here we report greater anaerobic C flow through sulfate reduction than through methanogenesis at all sites situated along a global atmospheric sulfur deposition gradient. Stoichiometric mass balance suggests that fermentation is a dominant anaerobic C mineralization pathway in unpolluted peatlands, while methanogenesis contributed minimally to total anaerobic carbon mineralization in these sites. Furthermore, global increases of atmospheric sulfur deposition minimize the impacts of climatic warming by simultaneously decreasing rates of methanogenesis while causing little change in rates of total anaerobic C mineralization in Sphagnum-dominated peatlands.","Carbon budget; Carbon-dioxide; Methanogenesis; Sphagnum-peatlands; Sulfate reduction","atmospheric deposition; carbon budget; carbon dioxide; freshwater; methanogenesis; peatland; sulfur; Sphagnum",,,,,,"Aselmann, I., Crutzen, P.J., Global distribution of natural freshwater wetlands and rice paddies, their net primary productivity, seasonality and possible methane emissions (1989) J. Atmos. Chem., 8, pp. 307-359; Badr, O., Probert, S.D., Atmospheric sulphur: Trends, sources, sinks and environmental impacts (1994) Appl. Energy, 47, pp. 1-67; Bartlett, K.B., Harriss, R.C., Review and assessment of methane emissions from Wetlands (1993) Chemosphere, 26, pp. 261-320; Bridgham, S.D., Updegraff, K., Pastor, J., Carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus mineralization in northern wetlands (1998) Ecology, 79, pp. 1545-1561; Bridgham, S.D., Ping, C.L., Richardson, J.L., Updegraff, K., Soils of peatlands: Histosols and gelisols (2000) Wetland Soils: Genesis, Hydrology, Landscapes, and Classification, pp. 343-370. , edited by J. L. Richardson and M. J. Vepraskas, CRC, Boca Raton, Fla; Conrad, R., Control of methane production in terrestrial ecosystems (1989) Exchange of Trace Gases Between Ecosystems and the Atmosphere, pp. 37-58. , edited by M. O. Andreae and D. S. Schimel, John Wiley, New York; Dise, N., Verry, E., Suppression of peatland methane emission by cumulative sulfate deposition in simulated acid rain (2001) Biogeochemistry, 53, pp. 143-160; Ecoclimatic regions of Canada (1989) Ecol. Land Class., , Ecoregions Working Group, Ser. 23, Environ. Can., Ottawa; Fauque, G.D., Ecology of sulfate reducing bacteria (1995) Sulfate Reducing Bacteria, pp. 217-244. , edited by L. Barton, Plenum Press, New York; Fung, I., John, P., Lerner, J., Matthews, E., Prather, M., Steele, L.P., Fraser, P.J., Global budgets of atmospheric methane: Results from a three-dimensional global model synthes